I feel your pain. Security is great until it starts feeling like a part-time job. Since you’re on Arch with Hyprland, you’ve already embraced the "manual but powerful" life, so let's get your SSH workflow as smooth as your window animations.

The standard solution is an SSH Agent. This lives in the background, holds your decrypted key in memory, and handles the "handshake" so you only type your passphrase once per session.

1. The "Hyprland Way": Keychain
On a tiling window manager like Hyprland, the most reliable tool is often keychain. It’s a front-end for ssh-agent that persists across different terminal windows.

The Setup:

Install it: sudo pacman -S keychain

Configure your shell: Add this to your .zshrc (or .bashrc):

Bash
eval $(keychain --eval --agents ssh id_ed25519)
The Result: The first time you open a terminal after booting, it will ask for your passphrase. Every terminal you open after that will just work.

2. The "Set and Forget": PAM-SSH-Add
If you want to be truly "bloody annoyed" no longer, you can set it up so that logging into your computer automatically unlocks your SSH key (provided your login password and SSH passphrase are the same).

Tool: pam_ssh_agent_auth

How it works: When you log in via your Display Manager (like SDDM or Greetd), it passess your password to the agent.

Caveat: This is a bit more involved to configure in /etc/pam.d/, but it's the gold standard for a "seamless" experience.

3. The Config Shortcut
Regardless of which agent you use, make sure your ~/.ssh/config file is optimized. You can tell SSH to always try the agent first:

Plaintext
Host *
  AddKeysToAgent yes
  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
A Note on Security
By using an agent, your decrypted key sits in RAM. This is generally very safe, but if you're working in a high-risk environment, you can add a timeout to your agent so it "forgets" the key after a few hours:
keychain --timeout 480 --eval id_ed25519 (where 480 is minutes).

