Link KeePassXC:

Open KeePassXC > Tools > Settings > SSH Agent.

Check "Enable SSH Agent integration".

Check "Use settings from the environment" (it should find your socket automatically).

Add your Key:

Create an entry for your SSH key.

Under the SSH Agent tab of that entry, point it to your id_ed25519 file (or attach it to the database).

Put your 25519 passphrase in the Password field of that entry.

The "Absolute Minimalist" Way: Systemd-creds
If you don't even want a GUI password manager, you can use Systemd-creds (which is already on your system because of systemd).

This allows you to "seal" your SSH passphrase to your hardware (TPM2 chip) or your user account.

